    <li>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>u(x)</m> and <m>v(x)</m> are Darboux integrable functions and that <m>v(a) = v(b) = 0</m>. Show that 
        <md>
          \int_a^b u(x) v'(x) dx = -\int_a^b u'(x) v(x) dx
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
         Find the mistake in the following ``Counterexample'' of Darboux's Theorem (Theorem 5.2.7 in the textbook, Theorem 13 in the notes):
      </p>

      <proof>
      <p>
        Let
        <md>
          g(x) = \begin{cases} 
      \hfill  1  \amp \text{ if $ 0 \leq x \leq 2$} \\
      \hfill  -1 \hfill \amp \text{ if $-2 \leq x &lt; 0$} 
  \end{cases}
        </md>
        and define 
        <md>
          G(x) = \int_{-2}^x g(t) dt
        </md>
        for <m>x \in [-2,2]</m>. Since <m>g(x)</m> has a single discontinuity, it is Darboux integrable and thus by part <m>2</m> of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus <m>G(x)</m> is a continuous function and <m>G'(x) = g(x)</m>. Hence <m>G'(-2) = -1</m> and <m>G'(2) = 1</m>. However, <m>-1 &lt; 0 &lt; 1</m>, but <m>G'(c) \neq 0</m> for any <m>c \in [-2,2]</m>. Thus <m>G(x)</m> is a counterexample of Darboux's Theorem. 
      </p>
      </proof>
    </li>

